<TEXT>
the bush administration is threatening a veto 
of the 1990 farm bill if the crop support programs in the version 
expected to be debated this week in the senate reaches the white 
house 
the announcement came in a letter monday to the senate from 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter who said the programs were 
too costly at a time when the government is trying to cut the 
budget deficit 
sen patrick leahy dvt chairman of the agriculture 
committee immediately criticized the letter as an eleventhhour 
threat aimed at killing the fiveyear bill as part of an 
international trade negotiating strategy being pursued by president 
bush and yeutter 
senate leaders have said they would try to begin debate on the 
bill by wednesday 
leahys committee has estimated that the commodity programs in 
the bill would cost 55 billion over five years but yeutter said 
its spending requirements amount to 59 billion 
this compares with an estimated 794 billion spent over the 
last five years under the 1985 law that expires this year 
the veto threat follows efforts by bush at the sevennation 
economic summit in houston last week to get the europeans to reduce 
subsidies on farm products that the united states considers 
distorting to the international marketplace 
a fiveyear farm bill could be viewed as limiting the promises 
negotiators could make to the other countries about us policy 
but members of the senate and house agriculture committees have 
said they would make necessary adjustments based on the outcome of 
the ongoing talks over the general agreement on tariffs and trade 
in geneva switzerland 
the administration has indicated support for a oneyear 
extension of the current farm law senate republican leader bob 
dole of kansas said on friday he would offer such legislation if 
the spending in the bill going to the floor is not reduced 
the administrations veto threat is a thinly veiled effort to 
kill the farm bill so the administration can cut a backroom deal 
in geneva out of sight of the american farmer said leahy 
yeutter didnt mention the trade talks in his letter he dwelled 
instead on the budget implications of the senates farm bill 
criticizing every subsidy program in the legislation 
from a budget standpoint the cost of the bill is excessive 
he said 
yeutter said that if the bill is sent to the president before 
budget talks with congress are completed and without substantial 
savings and a change in the price and income support programs 
the secretary of agriculture and the presidents other senior 
advisers would recommend that he bush veto the bill 
the government subsidizes farmers who produce wheat corn rice 
cotton soybeans sugar dairy products wool and mohair honey and 
peanuts either by direct payment or manipulation of the marketplace 
leahy said the administration had cooked up new numbers in 
estimating the bills impact on the budget 
the reality is that the senate farm bill is over 6 billion 
less than what the president proposed in january for current 
services he said 
