<TEXT>
an annual market survey by the agriculture 
department shows the rate of farmland sales through financial 
failure declined last year 
nationally voluntary and estate sales accounted for 70 percent 
of the farmland transfers in the latter part of 1989 compared with 
66 percent in the same period of 1988 
sales or transfers among family members accounted for 16 percent 
of the land transactions about the same as the preceding year the 
departments economic research service said 
another 11 percent represented foreclosure bankruptcy and 
condemnation sales and transfers against 15 percent in 1988 
while 3 percent fell into the other sales and transfers category 
the same as in 1988 the report said 
officials said the survey included information on nearly 6600 
farmland sales involving more than 2 million acres 
the research agencys annual farmland market survey was 
described in a new agricultural resources outlook report 
elaborating on figures announced in april that showed us farmland 
prices rose 4 percent in 1989 
a further gain of between 3 percent and 4 percent is forecast 
for 1990 based upon the current economic outlook 
the report said other farmers continue to buy most of the land 
sold during the year accounting for 59 percent of the purchases 
last year compared with 57 percent in 1988 
tenants made 12 percent of the purchases compared with 11 
percent the previous year nonfarmers accounted for 27 percent 
down from 29 percent in 1988 and retired farmers 2 percent 
unchanged 
shares among buyer groups have been fairly stable over the 
past several years the report said ten years ago 
owneroperators were involved in 50 percent of the reported 
purchases with tenants 15 percent retired farmers 2 percent 
and nonfarmers 33 percent accounting for the rest 
the report also noted that nearly 41 percent of all us 
farmland operated in 1989 was rented according to another survey 
on farm costs and returns 
leasing was most widespread in the corn belt northern plains 
southern plains and mississippi delta states where 50 to 55 
percent of all land operated was leased the report said in 
other regions the proportion of leasing ranged from 28 percent in 
the southeast to 35 percent in the mountain region 
tenants most often leased land on a cashrent basis accounting 
for 66 percent of all rented land last year thirty percent was 
rented for shares of production and 4 percent was rentfree 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the structure and volume of japans 
agricultural trade has changed substantially over the long haul 
despite a popular perception of inflexibility according to an 
agriculture department analyst 
rapidly changing economies in then soviet union and eastern 
europe have dominated the worlds attention says william coyle of 
usdas economic research service 
japan by contrast often appears reluctant to change because 
of persistent and large trade surpluses an inhospitable attitude 
about foreign investment and imports and a political system 
dominated for 35 years by one party he said 
but changes do occur in japan but they sometimes go unnoticed 
because they are slow and incremental 
bulk commodities such as grain soybeans cotton and tobacco 
still make up most of japans agricultural imports but coyle said 
valueadded products are accounting for a growing share 
tariff reductions deregulation of foreign cigarette imports and 
more beef and citrus since 1985 helped push japans valueadded 
imports to 12 billion in 1988 up 20 percent from 1970 
in 1988 when japans agricultural imports were valued at 272 
billion bulk commodities made up 554 percent of the total in 
1970 when they were worth 42 billion grains and other bulk 
items accounted for 798 percent 
coyle writing in a new outlook report on world agriculture 
said the changes have meant more meat less imported grain more 
cigarettes less leaf tobacco more finished textile products less 
raw fibers and more pasta and less wheat 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a package of queen honeybees from a 
90yearold monk in england is being added to the agriculture 
departments weaponry against the destructive tracheal mite 
the 15 queen bees from brother adam in buckfastleigh england 
will be used by scientists at the departments bee laboratory in 
baton rouge la to breed miteresistant strains 
ralph a bram of the departments agricultural research service 
said the breeding program will take two or three years if 
successful new queens will be distributed to bee breeders 
parasitic tracheal mites clog the breathing tubes of bees 
killing 80 percent or more of a hive 
brother adam a resident of the abbey since 1910 began keeping 
bees at age 16 the agency said he has written reports that his 
bees withstand mite attacks even when in identical environments 
other races and crosses collapsed midseason 
</TEXT>
