<TEXT>
the senate is deciding whether to force a vote 
on civil rights legislation with critics still warning that it 
would inevitably lead to racial and ethnic hiring quotas 
bargaining among the white house bill sponsors and conservative 
senators stretched into the early evening monday but failed to 
produce an agreement on the embattled civil rights bill 
provisions of the measure range from a ban on racial harassment 
in the workplace to punitive damages for victims of discrimination 
the most controversy has surrounded a provision that would 
require employers to end practices shown to be statistically 
discriminatory or prove in court that they were justified by 
business necessity 
senate minority leader bob dole rkan said talks over the 
last three weeks have produced many areas of common ground 
between the administration and the bills proponents here in 
congress 
but this common ground is shaky ground and it will collapse 
if the bills proponents do not show some willingness to address 
in very meaningful ways some very legitimate concerns raised by 
the president and his advisers dole added 
he said he favored a civil rights bill but could not accept the 
version currently under debate 
meanwhile majority leader george mitchell dmaine laid the 
groundwork for a vote today on whether to limit debate to 30 hours 
it would take 60 votes to succeed in such a move 
sen edward m kennedy dmass and other sponsors have been 
holding off on trying to force a vote while negotiating with the 
administration 
it appeared friday that kennedy and the administration might be 
close to an agreement friday and the massachusetts senator said one 
was likely this week before leaving for his camp david retreat 
friday president bush said he was encouraged by the turn the talks 
had taken 
the bill is aimed at reversing five supreme court decisions last 
year that civil rights forces say represented a severe setback for 
their cause 
before last years decision in the case of wards cove vs 
antonio involving hiring at a salmon cannery in alaska it was up 
to the employer to prove in court that a practice shown to be 
discriminatory was a matter of business necessity and therefore 
justified 
the wards cove decision reversed that and said those filing 
discrimination suits must prove that the practices involved were 
not matters of business necessity 
kennedys bill would place the burden back on the employer but 
critics say it would make it even easier to win a job 
discrimination suit than before the wards cove decision they say 
employers would be guaranteed to turn to the use of quotas to 
protect themselves from such suits 
business groups also are upset over a provision of the bill that 
would allow courts to award punitive damages to victims of bias in 
the workplace 
sen nancy kassebaum rkan on monday introduced a proposed 
compromise that appeared likely to gain support from lawmakers 
holding out against the kennedy version but wanting to prove that 
they were not opponents of civil rights 
kassebaum said in a statement that her measure would reinstate 
the legal language in use before the wards cove decision she said 
that provision forms an appropriate balance between the concerns 
voiced on both sides avoiding quotas and excessive litigation 
versus ensuring equal opportunity in the workplace 
she said her measure was designed to restore our civil rights 
laws to the same strength and clarity that existed before a series 
of supreme court decisions last year 
those decisions have significantly increased the difficulty of 
proving discrimination and if they are allowed to stand they will 
weaken our civil rights laws she said 
she said the other goal of her bill was to maintain the 
balance first struck by the 1964 civil rights act and to preserve 
the basic philosophy of conciliation cooperation and equitable 
relief that are the foundation of all of our civil rights laws 
</TEXT>
