fish oil sellers are under orders from the 
food and drug administration to stop claiming their capsules can 
help lower cholesterol and the chance of heart attacks 
fda spokesman bill grigg said the agency concluded after 
consulting with the national institutes of health that although 
some studies have suggested fish oil might be useful for 
cholesterol lowering there wasnt sufficient evidence for them 
to make these claims regarding the amount found in capsules 
the letters sent to 60 fish oil capsule makers monday are an 
extension of an earlier fda warning for them to stop claiming the 
capsules were good for arthritis and other disorders the companies 
agreed with that but argued that the cardiovascular benefits were 
wellenough established to justify the claim 
several studies in recent years have suggested that fish oils 
containing a component called omega3 such as those from mackerel 
and herring can lower blood pressure and cholesterol reduce 
damage from inflammatory processes such as arthritis and lower the 
chances of other problems such as diabetes and heart attacks 
grigg said the fda agrees that there are studies that show 
fish diets may be helpful 
we said its quite conceivable that further research might 
justify an assertion that the capsules provide health benefits 
grigg said 
but such results are several months if not more down the 
road he added 
it is the assertion of a health benefit that brings fish oil 
capsules under stringent drug regulation rules the manufacturers 
can continue selling their capsules as foods without health claims 
if the faa accepts them as generally recognized as safe grigg 
said 
this might be a simple matter for some products because for 
codliver oil and some of the others there is a good record 
grigg said 
