<DOCNO> AP900717-0063 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
olympic diving champion greg louganis sets a 
good athletic example for many youngsters for starters he 
cautions that they not just plunge in but think ahead 
know the water depth before you dive tops the list of 
louganis diving tips 
that sounds simple and in pools the water depth may be marked 
on the sid but just looking into the water can be deceptive and 
in lakes and ponds care is especially important 
rocks partly sunken logs and other hidden obstructions can lurk 
beneath the surface and the water may simply not be as deep as 
people think 
never dive where you dont know the depth or where there may be 
obstructions once a dive is started there is no time to change or 
think 
remember when diving down into water steer up with hands 
never dive into an aboveground pool or into the shallow end of 
any pool nine out of 10 diving injuries occur when people dive 
into water less than six feet deep according to the national 
swimming pool foundation 
often injuries follow when inexperienced people do back dives 
dive through objects such as inner tubes or try fancy dives 
one crucial warning never dive or swim alone 
anyone can get into trouble in the water and the best insurance 
policy is a friend to pull you out if necessary 
children are particularly vulnerable according to the national 
spa and pool institute but the safety measure that best protects 
them is simple a watchful adult on hand at all times 
nothing can replace a watchful parent grandparent neighbor or 
babysitter when it comes to make sure a child is safe in the water 
its easy for horseplay to get out of hand so the american 
academy of pediatrics urges setting rules around water running 
pushing and similar roughhousing should be banned 
be sure everyone leaves the water and finds a safe shelter in 
the event of a thunderstorm also 
good fences make safe pools ensuring that people cant get to 
the pool fall in and drown when no one is available to save them 
many communities have laws setting minimum sizes for pool 
fences at the least the spa and pool institute recommends a 
barrier tall enough to prevent youngsters from climbing over and 
dont place tables chairs and other items nearby that could be 
used to climb over the fence 
doors gates and other entry points need secure latches 
finally post the number for emergency assistance near the 
telephone and learn to administer cardiopulmonary resuscitation 
just in case in fact make sure anyone who supervises the pool 
knows cpr 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

