<TEXT>
raymond dunn jr turned 16 tuesday but 
the profoundly retarded birthday boy feasted not on cake to which 
he is allergic but on the days greatest gift the bland brown 
infant formula that keeps him alive 
gerber products co which stopped making the meatbased formula 
in 1985 resumed production two months ago after raymonds doctors 
said he would die without it gerber employees volunteered to make 
a batch on their own time and on june 26 the dunns received a 
twoyear supply free of charge 
gerber says babies are our business but raymonds their 
business too said carol dunn who spent five years trying to 
get the company to retool for a market of one 
the dunns celebrate raymonds birthdays quietly yet thankfully 
because each is one more than they were told to expect after 
raymond was born with a broken skull and a brain that had been 
deprived of oxygen 
at 16 raymond is getting mail from navy recruiters and college 
admissions offices but he rarely leaves his house in this village 
in the catskills 
as he sits in his wheelchair or lies on his special floor mat 
raymond moves only with the help of others and sees only shadows 
his expression ranges from a painful grimace to a slight smile he 
snorts gurgles wheezes and occasionally burps 
he weighs 32 pounds and his twisted cramped body is 4 feet 
long he suffers 15 to 20 major seizures a day and sleeps two or 
three hours a night if at all his asthma makes each breath a 
struggle phlegm plugs repeatedly hospitalize him and threaten to 
kill him 
raymond the dunns only child also is allergic to the foods 
that help most children grow but he always was sustained by 
gerbers mbf meatbased formula 
when gerber decided to drop the product five years ago mrs 
dunn was unable to find or create any substitute that did not make 
raymond sick frantic she hunted down every can she could find 
and gerber kept passing along its own backlog 
by july 1988 gerber ran out of mbf leaving raymond with less 
than two years supply 
supported by the state association for retarded children mrs 
dunn begged gerber to make more mbf and began a mail campaign 
asking others to pressure the company finally the companys 
research director gave in 
since the nation learned of how a mothers devotion moved a 
large corporation mrs dunn and her husband raymond sr a car 
salesman have received a shopping bag full of mail a sunday 
school class sent a check for 28 a dealer in rare baseball cards 
offered raymond any card he wanted the rev raymond dunn no 
relation told mrs dunn that when her son finally dies you will 
have a saint in heaven 
meanwhile at gerber volunteers in the research division put 
their own projects on hold hauled out old equipment and devoted 
several thousand square feet and several days of production space 
and time to raymonds supply of mbf 
it arrived in yankee lake just in time the dunns had about two 
dozen cans of the old formula enough to last through the end of 
july 
each july 17 mrs dunn worries that this birthday will be 
raymonds last so she follows the same ritual 
she takes last years birthday number candles from the tea cup 
over the sink and burns them down then she takes the candle 
numbers from this years cake and places them in the cup where 
they sit for the next 12 months raymond wears the same gold 
cardboard kings crown with each year marked on a point on the 
crown 
but even these rituals are touched by sadness there are only 
two points left on the crown and mrs dunn has not had to let it 
out in many years because raymonds head grows very little 
what is most remarkable about raymond is not his condition but 
the care he receives his mother and a platoon of teachers and 
helpers caress him almost constantly they feed him seven times 
daily and brush his teeth after each feeding 
raymond sleeps in his parents bed often between them he 
receives about a dozen different medications some several times a 
day his mothers calendar has no luncheon dates or hairdressers 
appointments it is devoted entirely to charting the times and 
dosages of just one asthma remedy 
but the dunns say his birthday reminds them that life at its 
most marginal at its most precarious is life at its most 
meaningful 
when raymond was an infant they were urged to institutionalize 
him told that keeping him home would burn them out and ruin their 
marriage 
we knew wed have to pay a price and the price has been 
hard mrs dunn says ive given up a normal life but raymond 
gives me a lot of joy does it outweigh the sorrow no but he is 
my son and if i had put raymond away the price would have been 
even higher 
</TEXT>
