the social security administrations new 
telephone system is leaving many people waiting in vain for their 
calls to be returned government auditors said tuesday 
the general accounting office said that in some types of cases 
42 percent of callers never received the followup calls they were 
promised when they dialed social securitys tollfree 800 number 
social security follows up 97 percent of the time in other 
categories the report said 
it is difficult to avoid the conclusion that the social 
security 800 system is not a working number or at least that it is 
not working very well said rep andy jacobs jr dind 
chairman of the house ways and means social security subcommittee 
gao an arm of congress began investigating the phone system 
after social security blocked telephone access to its local field 
offices social security officials insisted that requiring that all 
calls be made to the 800 number would improve service 
jacobs said the gao study offered proof that service had not 
been improved 
while it may save time for social security workers jacobs said 
it wastes the time of people the government is supposed to be 
serving 
he said 800number operators lack training and expertise to 
answer nonroutine calls although its far easier to get through 
to the 800 number than it was earlier this year jacobs said a 
caller still will get a busy signal 35 percent of the time 
social security spokesman frank battistelli said the agency 
would not comment because it had not been given a copy of the gao 
report 
however he said that at least 80 percent of problems or 
questions posed in calls to the 800 number are settled on the spot 
without the need for any call back or referral to a field office 
even after repeated unsuccessful attempts to get back to a 
caller social security offices dont let a case slip through the 
cracks battistelli said 
we then send a letter asking the caller to get back in touch 
with us he said 
social security expects to receive as many as 70 million calls 
this year gao estimated that only about 5 percent require 
referrals 
gao acknowledged the difficulty in trying to get back to a 
caller in doing its survey gao said its workers were unable to 
make contact in five attempts with many of those who had called the 
800 number 
