<TEXT>
flaws in the food and drug administrations 
regulation of medical devices may allow unsafe products on the 
market witnesses told a house panel on tuesday 
investigations by the inspector general of the health and human 
services department suggest the fdas regulatory system may prevent 
the agency from detecting device problems early and acting 
promptly inspector general richard kusserow said 
kusserow said the problems with the medical device approval 
process parallel what we encountered in our extensive reviews of 
the generic drug division which turned up evidence that generic 
drug companies had cheated on tests required to win fda approval 
and bribed fda officials 
although our findings here are similar we have no evidence of 
these vulnerabilities manifesting themselves in any detected 
criminal wrongdoing kusserow told the house energy and commerce 
health subcommittee 
the inspector general said that in addition to needing more 
internal controls over the approval system the fda also needs 
stronger authority to remove defective devices from the marketplace 
rep john dingell dmich chairman of the committee said 
it is clear that the current statute does not adequately protect 
the public from unnecessary risks in addition the fda lacks the 
resources and the authority to enforce the law 
dingell and rep henry waxman dcalif chairman of the health 
subcommittee have introduced legislation to overhaul the law 
governing regulation of medical devices 
it would require closer scrutiny of the most dangerous devices 
and require hospitals and other major medical device users to 
report deaths and other serious problems with medical devices to 
the fda it also would give the fda more authority to remove 
products from the market 
more than 1700 medical devices are available in the united 
states representing an industry of more than 17 billion a year 
said carl wisler of the general accounting office 
