<TEXT>
people who eat too much fat and salt and dont 
exercise enough already may know better but a fiveyear research 
project shows these destructive habits can be discouraged 
scientists said 
there may be as many as 525 people alive today in salinas and 
monterey calif who would have died during the past 10 years if 
it hadnt been for specially designed health education programs 
there said dr john w farquhar of stanford universitys school of 
medicine 
methods do exist for selfimprovement farquhar said in a 
telephone interview monday 
after five years of community education farquhar said the 
average plasma cholesterol level among residents in salinas and 
monterey was 2 percent below that of people in modesto and san luis 
obispo which were used for comparison he said the pulse rate was 
3 percent lower the smoking rate 13 percent lower 
these figures mask the studys true importance farquhar said 
because people with higher levels would have experienced more 
dramatic declines 
using a method developed by other researchers the data from 
salinas and monterey translates to a 15 percent improvement in the 
mortality rate and a 16 percent decline in heart attack risks 
billions of dollars could be saved annually by this kind of 
reduction in heart attacks nationally said researchers who 
reported their findings in wednesdays issue of the journal of the 
american medical association 
because so many people continue their unhealthy habits despite 
the risks farquhar and his associates reasoned that a program 
going beyond mere education was needed 
so they prepared a special series of radio television and 
newspaper announcements and developed classes meetings mailings 
and other approaches for delivering their message 
the idea was not only to instruct residents on whats healthy 
but also to train them on how to make changes 
if you want to start a walking program where to you get the 
shoes what kind of shoes do you get and how do you get the friend 
down the block to go with you farquhar said illustrating the 
kinds of practical questions his program sought to answer 
or how do you get a healthy meal at a restaurant without 
being obnoxious he said we got down to these kinds of 
specifics 
twice a week for a little more than five years residents of 
salinas and monterey were indoctrinated with this kind of 
information 
if the 15 percent decline in mortality rate proves accurate 
its far better than farquhars expectation we would have been 
satisfied by 5 percent he said 
the stanford researchers plan to count the number of deaths in 
monterey salinas modesto and san luis obispo to establish a more 
precise mortality rate the 15 percent cited in the study is an 
estimate based on the improvement in cholesterol blood pressure 
and other health data 
the study is very impressive said thomas m lasater a 
community health educator at brown university involved in similar 
research at memorial hospital of rhode island in pawtucket 
he said the direct medical costs for people with heart disease 
is equivalent to 300 to 400 a year for every person in the united 
states 
lasater said that if the improvement in mortality rate proves 
accurate the nation could save 11 billion or more a year if 
farquhars methods could be applied across the country 
the cost of farquhars program came to about 4 per person in 
the cities each year farquhar estimated that this is 4 percent of 
the annual per capita expenditure for cigarettes 
what were trying to do is get out a message of hope to policy 
planners health specialists educators and others that methods do 
exist to help communities help themselves he said 
