<TEXT>
thousands of residents of this 
devastated city endured severe food water and power shortages on 
tuesday a day after a major earthquake nearly isolated this luxury 
mountain resort from the outside world 
the quake which measured 77 on the richter scale killed 82 
people here and more than 195 elsewhere in the philippines most of 
the baguio casualties died in the rubble of four luxury hotels and 
23 other buildings that were severely damaged hundreds more are 
believed still trapped in debris 
president corazon aquino flew to baguio early wednesday to 
inspect the damage 
i never thought in my entire life that i could see such 
destruction said ed pangilinan a spokesman for the defense 
department who accompanied defense secretary fidel ramos to the 
city 110 miles north of manila 
he said townspeople lined the streets begging for food as ramos 
party drove past philippine television stations reported 
widespread looting in the city wednesday 
baguio was the town most heavily damaged by the earthquake 
which left at least 279 dead 
us embassy spokesman stanley schrager said about 1500 
americans live in baguio but there were no reports of deaths or 
injuries among them 
the citys two funeral parlors have more business than they can 
handle and have refused to accept more dead during his tuesday 
tour ramos said he would ask for preservatives to be flown into 
the city so the dead could be safely stored until they can be 
properly buried 
tuesday rep raul roco assistant house majority leader stood 
helpless outside the nevada hotel which was ripped in half by the 
quake shouting to his wife who was trapped inside 
a frustrated roco urged cadets of the philippine military 
academy located here to help him rescue his wife 
sir we want to help you but what can we do how can we with 
our bare hands one cadet replied 
the isolation of this mountain town which helped make it a 
favorite resort among filipinos seeking to escape the summer heat 
hampered rescue effforts 
mondays quake closed the airport knocked out telephone water 
and electricity services and buried the access roads under tons of 
mud and stone 
the military said it was unable to bring cranes tractors and 
other heavy equipment to the city because of the landslides the 
landslides also trapped hundreds of people in passenger buses 
trucks and private cars 
food and fuel supplies in the city were reportedly running low 
col bienvenido liclican spokesman for the military rescue team 
said the search for survivors has to be suspended at night because 
there is no electricity to power searchlights 
officials said it may take up to six months to clear the main 
highway linking baguio with the rest of the country 
commercial life in this city of 120000 has all but ceased most 
stores are closed and residents are running out of food one 
grocery store opened tuesday but quickly shut its doors after 
setting off a stampede 
only one of the eight service stations is operating and 
motorists must line up to buy the 450 of gas that rationing 
permits them 
since the quake struck thousands have been living in their cars 
or camping out in the citys park fearful of returning to their 
homes 
a us air force engineering team joined the search for up to 
1000 people believed trapped in the rubble of 27 buildings 
the damaged buildings included four luxury hotels that cracked 
under the force of the quake the entire front section of the hyatt 
terraces baguio which featured a floortoroof inner atrium 
tumbled down on the lobby area trapping an estimated 150 people 
