<TEXT>
a nicaraguan diplomat who allegedly recruited 
other embassy workers to smuggle heroinfilled suitcases into the 
united states and australia was arrested in tokyo on tuesday 
authorities said 
william tapia recently promoted to the no 2 position in the 
nicaraguan embassy in tokyo was charged in a federal indictment 
unsealed tuesday with conspiring to smuggle heroin worth up to 21 
million from thailand to new york 
he was dismissed from his job by the nicaraguan government and 
arrested by japanese authorities acting on a warrant issued in 
brooklyn said us attorney andrew maloney 
in managua the nicaraguan foreign ministry said it had stripped 
tapia of his diplomatic immunity at the request of the us and 
japanese governments so that he could be arrested 
tapia 47 will be extradited to new york within 45 days to 
stand trial maloney said 
tapia worked since at least 1986 with two prominent hong kong 
dealers to smuggle heroin to new york and sydney australia said 
assistant us attorney cathy palmer 
the indictment filed feb 6 in new york after an 18month 
investigation charges tapia arranged two trips in 1987 for a 
guatemalan diplomat jorge rueda to smuggle a total of 125 pounds 
of china white heroin to new york 
tapia received between 300000 and 400000 per trip for 
recruiting the diplomats he is suspected of arranging at least 
four more trips maloney said 
all of the diplomats recruited were from central or south 
american countries and stationed in tokyo he said 
rueda was arrested in australia in april 1988 on heroin 
importation charges and subsequently convicted 
a foreign ministry official in japan speaking on condition of 
anonymity said tapia first came to japan as the embassys cultural 
attache in 1968 he resigned in 1979 but rejoined the embassy as 
first secretary in june 1986 and was recently promoted to 
counselor the official said 
palmer said tapias arrest may not significantly affect the 
amount of heroin on the streets in new york but that it would make 
it harder for hong kong drug lords to bring it in 
it takes out a very secure method for smuggling using 
diplomats she said they are subject to almost no scrutiny 
upon arrival 
us customs agents normally do not inspect the luggage of 
diplomats because of their status maloney said 
tapia faces at least 10 years and up to life in prison if 
convicted of all charges 
the investigation is continuing and more arrests were possible 
palmer said also involved are the federal multiagency southeast 
asian heroin task force and authorities in hong kong australia and 
japan 
