<TEXT>
american makers of new type display screens 
for use in electronic gear of the future accused major japanese 
competitors tuesday of unfair pricecutting on us sales 
a petition filed by the advanced display manufacturers of 
america asked the government to order penalty duties as high as 318 
percent on japanese imports that it said violate this countrys 
antidumping laws 
dumping is selling at less than production costs or home market 
prices to capture an unfair share of a market 
the petition filed with the us commerce department named 12 
japanese electronic companies including sharp corp matsushita 
electrical industrial co and hitachi ltd those three were 
identified as the major suppliers to the united states with a 
total of 385 percent of the us market in recent years 
japanese imports have captured 90 percent of the fastgrowing 
multimilliondollar american market for flat panel display screens 
a technology originated in this country the petition claimed the 
other firms named were toshiba corp fujitsu ltd hoshiden 
electronics co kyocera corp matsuhita electronics corp nec 
corp optrex corp seiko epson corp and seiko indstruments and 
electronics ltd 
the american manufacturers said the petition would also be filed 
with the us international trade commission the two agencies may 
decide to hold public hearings in a procedure that lasts about a 
year before the final decision on whether to charge penalty duties 
flat panel display screens are replacing the larger conventional 
cathode ray tubes that now form the screens of television 
receivers word processors and computers aircraft control panels 
medical imaging devices and other equipment the technology would 
be incorporated in highdefinition television 
members of american manufacturers association include planar 
systems plasmasco inc ovonic imaging systems inc the cherry 
corp electroplasma inc photonics technology inc and 
magnascreen corp 
