<TEXT>
inspections by the food and drug 
administration of the top 13 laboratories that conduct a key test 
on generic drugs found problems at two an agency spokesman said 
tuesday 
the problems were most severe at biodecision laboratories in 
pittsburgh where all but two of 13 studies reviewed by the 
inspectors violated fda regulations or fell short of accepted 
laboratory practice said fda spokesman don mclearn 
problems were also found at the university of tennessee college 
of pharmacy in memphis mclearn said he said he did not know the 
specific problems there but he said theyre minimal theyre 
clearly not to the degree as the one in pittsburgh 
the inspections at the 13 labs which conduct 95 percent of the 
bioequivalency studies done on generic drugs were conducted as 
part of a followup to disclosures of fraud and corruption in the 
generic drug industry last year eleven of the labs had no 
problems mclearn said 
bioequivalency testing is aimed at showing that a candidate 
generic drug reaches the same concentration in the bloodstream as 
the patented drug for which it would be sold as a substitute after 
the patent expires 
the inspection at biodecision was conducted also as a followup 
to anonymous allegations of wrongdoing according to the fda 
inspection report the document said allegations of poor science 
were found to be supportable evidence of fraud conspiracy and 
conflict of interest was not 
however rep john dingell dmich chairman of the house 
energy and commerce investigations subcommittee wants the fda to 
conduct more intensive examinations of the studies done by these 
labs on generic drugs that were approved based on those studies 
dingell in a letter monday also asked health and human 
services secretary louis sullivan to instruct the fda to come up 
with a plan by aug 8 to determine the validity of the biodecision 
studies 
biodecision has conducted 20 percent to 30 percent of the 
bioequivalency studies that have resulted in approved generic 
drugs dingell said 
given the impact on the generic industry from corruption found 
to date this latest revelation concerning biodecision of 
impropriety is truly calamitous dingell said 
mclearn said the fda has not responded to dingells request for 
more investigation of biodecisions studies or his request for more 
intensive investigations at the other testing labs 
dingell said that since the biodecision inspection was triggered 
by fraud allegations he doubted the inspections at the other labs 
were as intense 
mclearn said biodecision promised to correct the flaws 
company president robert lecher did not return a telephone for 
comment on tuesday but he was quoted by the washington post as 
saying we view the entire process as very constructive and have 
taken it extremely seriously we dont take issue or disagree with 
any of the observations 
in memphis gil hayes a spokesman for the college of pharmacy 
said we have no information as to what the nature of the 
deficiency might be well investigate that we feel quite 
confident that our college of pharmacy has performed an exemplary 
service over many years 
