<TEXT>
attorneys for floridas death row 
inmates have seized on a botched execution arguing their clients 
would be burned alive in the states electric chair 
they contend the electric chair is broken and have produced 
photographs of executed inmates in an attempt to prove that killing 
a person in the chair amounts to unconstitutionally cruel and 
unusual punishment two statepaid attorneys have even offered 
4000 to fix the 66yearold chair 
the issue has been raised in five appeals by death row inmates 
since the states last execution may 4 courts delayed the 
executions of all five but in only one case did the chair issue 
play a role in a decision 
two other courts rejected the defective chair issue 
the efforts began after the electrocution of jesse tafero 
flames and smoke shot from under the headpiece he wore 
the state department of corrections and gov bob martinez have 
maintained that tafero died instantly and that the fire was caused 
by a new synthetic sponge under the headpiece instead of natural 
sponge used in other executions 
the defense lawyers contend that tafero was burned alive and 
that anyone else put to death in the chair would be subjected to 
the same torturous fate thus violating the constitutional ban 
against cruel and unusual punishment 
the faultychair issue was raised for the fifth time in an 
appeal filed with the florida supreme court for jerry white who 
was scheduled for execution wednesday at 701 am 
the court on tuesday rejected whites claims but gave him his 
second 24hour stay in as many days 
his attorneys then turned to us district judge patricia 
fawsett in orlando who also rejected his claims in an order issued 
late tuesday his case now goes to the 11th circuit court of 
appeals in atlanta whites execution was rescheduled for thursday 
at 701 am 
white 42 was condemned for shooting a customer to death during 
the 1981 robbery of a small grocery store in the central florida 
town of taft 
the issue of the chairs condition was raised in the case of 
judi buenoano who was granted an indefinite delay by a federal 
appeals court 
the electric chair argument has been rejected in her appeals by 
a federal judge in orlando and by the state supreme court which 
said the chairs condition should be decided by the executive 
rather than the judicial branch 
defense attorneys argue that a broken head electrode lowered the 
level of electricity sent through taferos body from a fatal 2400 
volts to as low as 90 or 100 volts witnesses saw tafero move and 
breathe after the first two jolts of electricity he was pronounced 
dead after the third 
color photographs of the last nine men executed in florida have 
been included in the defense motions in an attempt to show that the 
damage done to taferos skull and leg differs from the damage done 
to the head and legs of the eight men executed before him 
