<TEXT>
when some of the best minds and the most 
powerful legislative bodies cannot resolve budget deficits 
taxpayers might have to seek new ways to pressure elected officials 
here are a few suggestions gleaned from various sources 
question the elected persons patriotism 
since deficits incurred by one generation are a tax and economic 
liability on future generations the effect is that of taxation 
without representation a a violation of the american principle of 
fair play 
according to the patriots of the american revolution taxation 
without representatation is tyranny oppression a violation of the 
rights of free men and women millions of future generations 
therefore are unfairly taxed 
economist e erich heinemann poses the problem and challenges 
succinctly unless the generation that consumes federal services 
also pays for them there will never be a durable majority to limit 
the size of government 
apply psychological pressure on elected officials 
individuals who consistently habitually spend beyond their 
means are viewed in a variety of negative ways 
many people see them as irresponsible and shiftless some view 
them as ignorant some consider them immoral in serious cases 
psychological counseling and therapy are often recommended 
it has been recommended that the same attitudes be applied to 
political spending and spenders since public image is essential to 
political survival the fear of being branded might stir a 
politicians survival instincts 
publicize the historical record publicize the broken promises 
attempts to cut budget deficits through higher taxes have a long 
record of failure so have socalled budget summits and promises 
it is an old political tradition to be against taxes but somehow 
taxes continue to rise 
generally speaking additional revenues from tax increases have 
been used to justify more spending when the government raises a 
dollar in revenues congress spends a dollar fifty president 
bush once explained 
regarding promises citizens for a sound economy an 
independent nonprofit research group reminded members that a 
1987 agreement between the white house and congress to limit 
spending growth led instead to quickened spending 
that agreement called for restraining spending increases to 50 
billion in 1988 and 1989 but in those two years spending increased 
by 139 billion 
it provoked the tax foundation independent nonprofit 
research oriented to warn of tax summitry by the light of 
recent budget summit history it said any deficit reduction 
deal could be a bad deal for taxpayers 
a foundation study found that in the 1980s the fiscal years 
that were not preceded by budget summits actually resulted in the 
most real deficit reduction 
remind voters that washington is a somewhat ineffective spender 
of money 
robert woodson jr congressional liaison for the national 
center for neighborhood enterprise which promotes the idea of 
selfhelp contends that social spending has empowered bureaucrats 
but not necessarily the poor 
its been estimated that 70 cents of every federal dollar 
spent on social service programs goes to the people agencies and 
organizations who serve the poor he states adding 
the big spenders in congress should be asking themselves now 
why hasnt the face of poverty changed 
many other suggestions are heard every day demand explanations 
expose selfish specialinterest spending proposals publicize 
waste encourage the development of a returnoninvestment guide to 
government spending 
all the ideas circulating seem to have one common theme to 
again make it politically unpalatable for elected officials to 
overspend 
