<TEXT>
danny oflaherty has just finished a rousing 
rendition of kelly the boy from killeen a barmaid gives him 
several slips of paper some folded around money he reads them and 
goes back to the mike at his irish pub in the french quarter 
weve been getting a lot of requests for danny boy we dont 
do that we only do the right stuff he tells the audience if 
youll read the literature at your table youll understand 
danny boy isnt the only tune nixed by oflaherty he also 
rejects when irish eyes are smiling and other overplayed ersatz 
irish tunes 
thats not ireland he said theres nothing wrong with 
those songs we just have something better 
opened in december the irish channel is only one block from the 
mississippi river in a sprawling old building with a courtyard 
separating two very different bars 
one is the ballad room featuring regular performances by 
oflaherty who spent three years touring with the irish minstrels 
and 16 years with his own trio the celtic folk a group that has 
10 albums and has played for presidents and the pope and in 
festivals as far away as israel 
the other is called the informer the bigger room across the 
courtyard it has a jukebox a television and four dart boards 
you can sit and talk as loudly as you want in the informer or in 
the courtyard but if you insist on talking out in the ballad room 
especially during some of the more poignant songs youll be asked 
to leave 
its probably the most unmannerly thing anyone could do talk 
while other people are performing said oflaherty 
but he acknowledges few other bars or pubs have such a 
requirement especially not in the boisterous french quarter 
maybe we have to open up a university in america so people can go 
to university and learn how to listen 
the amplification from speakers hung at what would be ceiling 
level if the second floor of the ballad room hadnt been torn out 
is loud enough to cover most quiet conversations in fact although 
you see mouths moving during singalong choruses you dont hear 
anyone but oflaherty until he stops to listen 
people drinking guinness harp double diamond carlsberg and 
miller lite not everybody likes to drink irish said the 
bartender at the 25 or so little tables include tourists and 
locals whitehaired couples and young adults with children 
oflaherty learned how to listen to sing and to play guitar 
mandolin accordion banjo harmonica and tin whistle in galway and 
his home island of innishmor off the galway coast he left in 
september 1970 to work for his uncles construction company in 
chicago he played and sang on weekends and about six months after 
he arrived the irish minstrels asked him to audition 
he toured with them for three years in early 1974 tired of 
airports he decided to settle in washington with his first wife 
i quit the music business for six weeks thats all i could 
last he said 
a woman hired him to play at her wedding oflaherty and his 
brother patrick borrowed a mandolin and a guitar three weeks 
later they were hired as the weekend entertainment at the 
dubliner which had just opened on capitol hill 
they decided to get away from pseudoirish schmaltz and rabid 
paeans to the irish republican army during the early 80s when 
they were performing at clubs and folk festivals around the east 
coast 
we were doing antiwar when it wasnt kosher said 
oflaherty 
patrick oflaherty is currently touring with a group called the 
gaelic shores and welsh harpist robin jamesjones shares the irish 
channel stage 
oflahertys emphasis on folk music doesnt mean he refuses to 
sing anything thats not irish or even songs that arent ancient 
and anonymous 
an evening in the ballad room is likely to include and the 
band played waltzing matilda an antiwar song about the battle 
of gallipoli and a spectacularly nonirish childrens tune called 
waltzing with bears as well as wild mountain thyme or 
the maid of fiveeo 
so whats an irish pub doing in the french quarter 
i dont find a bar like this surprising for a city that has 
five or seven st patricks day parades said don jennings a 
member of the ancient order of hibernians and the irish channel st 
patricks day committee 
perhaps more to the point the brothers and danny oflahertys 
wife susan like the city where an invitation for a bar gig 
during the 1984 worlds fair wound up stretching into a twoyear 
stint that soon was followed by another 
when they left they missed new orleans oflaherty said 
we didnt realize how lucky we were to live in new orleans or 
how nice it was until we left he said the other reason my 
wife and i before we left new orleans we lost twins theyre 
buried here in new orleans 
they returned in 1989 to open a pub as a home base for the 
celtic folk and as a living that didnt call for quite so much 
touring 
new orleans french spanish and africanamerican heritage is 
well known the irishness of the city is quiet once you research 
and dig down deep theres a lot of things the irish have done in a 
very positive manner in this city oflaherty said 
irish immigrants dug the canal after which canal street is 
named many believe they gave new orleans the accent known locally 
as da yat axsent a very close cousin to da way dey talk in 
noo yawk where irish immigrants also settled and they settled the 
irish channel along the riverfront 
oflaherty said he wanted to make his pub a center for that 
history as well as for the older irish heritage of his native 
land however he said he was advised against actually opening a 
bar in the irish channel because too few people would find it 
the bar has broken even most months he said though unluckily 
it opened in december when new orleans went through one of its 
worst freezes ever june was also rough the number of tourists 
and conventions had begun to slack off and the groups that did 
come to town included the national baptist convention 
coming attractions include concerts by tommy makem the clancy 
brothers and bluegrass fiddler kenny kosek who has recorded with 
jerry garcia and laurie anderson as well as the celtic folk 
oflaherty also would like to have a pub theater but thats 
still a dream 
we havent even reached what we want to do yet he said 
weve got to crawl before we walk 
