<TEXT>
ask dean brackley why he is going to el salvador 
to take the place of a murdered priest why he will give up a 
secure life in academia and he just gazes at the lush campus of 
fordham university 
i need to be close to the struggle for life and death he 
says it just isnt happening here 
it is happening he says in el salvador torn by a 10year 
civil war among the casualties six jesuit priests taken from 
their beds and shot in the back of the head nov 16 at the central 
america university 
the murder of the priests affected me deeply said brackley 
43 one of six priests chosen from around the world to replace 
their fallen brothers he leaves monday 
in san salvador where he has traveled twice before brackley 
will teach philosophy and religion to graduate students at the 
university and oversee a large rural parish in jayaque 45 minutes 
west of the city 
among the priests chosen by the university and the head of the 
jesuits in rome is another american charles beirne an 
administrator at santa clara university the others are a canadian 
a mexican a spaniard and a salvadoran 
we know it will be dangerous and were not going down there to 
commit suicide brackley said but the truth has to be told 
the slayings of the jesuits their cook and her 16yearold 
daughter underscore the dangers facing hundreds of clerics working 
in salvadors shantytowns 
since 1980 when el salvadors leftist rebels began fighting a 
succession of usbacked governments 72000 salvadorans have died 
in the war at least 30000 died at the hands of rightwing death 
squads human rights groups say 
some clerics who work among the dispossessed are viewed as 
subversives by the military and conservative government and as 
enemies by the far right which considers them marxist ideologues 
since 1980 16 including archbishop oscar arnulfo romero have 
been slain 
the leftleaning clerics maintain that the civil war arose from 
vast social injustice and that only by addressing its causes can it 
be resolved but the armed forces contend the revolution is fueled 
by communist forces outside the country 
news of the predawn massacre of the jesuits initially stunned 
the world and prompted calls from some us congressmen to 
reconsider aid to el salvador eight months later although an 
investigation continues no soldier has been tried an officer 
never has been convicted of human rights abuse in el salvador 
which receives 1 million in us aid each day 
brackley said he first was struck by the social inequities of 
life not in central america but in his hometown of troy ny a 
declining milltown 
as a selfconscious little boy i was stunned by poverty he 
recalled he also recognized early on that he was blessed with a 
quixotic temperament given to adventure rather than boredom even 
if it hurts 
brackley joined the jesuits when he was 18 but after graduating 
from boston college he had what he termed a crisis of faith 
and went to work on new york citys impoverished lower east side 
there he learned spanish and helped found a junior high school 
for promising boys from the community 
in the early 1970s as he wrestled with the churchs role in 
society brackley met dorothy day the charismatic cofounder of 
the catholic workers movement he remembers her simple advice to 
him stay close to the people 
the encounter with day taught him confusion doesnt clear up 
until you make a commitment brackley said he said he also 
learned he had something to contribute to the poor and their 
cause 
subsequently brackley reaffirmed his commitment to seminary in 
berkeley calif while doing research he engaged in what he calls 
theological tourism he worked as a carpenter in puerto rico 
and studied in peru 
it was in latin america he was introduced to liberation 
theology the doctrine that champions the poor and oppressed in 
countries where mass poverty coexists with the opulence of a tiny 
minority since it evolved in the 1960s the doctrine has 
splintered the roman catholic establishment 
brackley returned to the united states and while completing a 
doctorate in theology at the university of chicago took courses in 
political science 
i had found out in latin america that god was concerned with 
suffering he said but what was gods view of the 
international monetary fund 
with a doctorate in hand brackley returned to new york and 
worked as a priest and organizer for the south bronx people for 
change a churchsponsored group that sprang up in 1979 to force 
city support for the abandoned community 
in september he took a teaching post at fordham but blanca 
ramirez who heads people for change said there are two places 
brackley is truly happy the south bronx or el salvador 
in the south bronx i learned how to survive which meant 
having a sense of humor resilience and humility brackley said 
i learned who i was and what my mission was 
