metcalf sold a vacuumtype machine called a nesbitt bugcatcher 
it helped he recalls but you couldnt get em all 
even today crop losses and control costs amount to 300 million 
a year and the bill comes to 12 billion altogether since the 
weevil entered texas in 1892 the cotton council estimates 
so there was a mixture of hope and skepticism when the us 
department of agriculture launched an experimental eradication 
effort in a small area of virginia and north carolina in 1978 
fear no weevil became the projects unofficial motto 
instead of farmbyfarm measures it used an area approach 
working from weevilfree zones the pilot program applied weekly 
doses of insecticide from september to the first frost to reduce 
the number of overwintering weevils in spring bug traps 
revealed surviving populations which were sprayed after the third 
year program officials merely mopped up spot reinfestations 
the pilot program was expanded to all of north and south 
carolina in 1983 with farmers and the government sharing costs 
its quite clear that biologically it was successful says 
