<TEXT>
after 30 million of repairs the exxon valdez 
is due back at sea in august with a new crew new steel in its 
shredded hull new ports of call in the middle east and a new name 
exxon mediterranean but no such industrywide makeover has 
occurred to limit oil spills and their damage 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
it seemed like a maritime version of murphys 
law 
the wayward exxon valdez plowed into bligh reef then three 
shipwrecks oiled three waterways within 12 hours last june 
the american trader ran over its anchor and gashed itself the 
bt nautilus was one of three spills in three months in the new york 
city area the mega borg caught fire in the gulf of mexico and on 
and on and on 
but these accidents all within 15 months of each other are 
more than just a run of bad luck systemwide flaws in the way 
tankers are built operated and monitored contribute to accidents 
according to records and interviews with industry experts 
on an average of five days out of seven last year a tanker ran 
aground hit another ship or a dock broke apart sprung a leak 
exploded or had some other kind of mishap according to coast guard 
records 
a coast guard report on tanker safety cited formidable 
problems in regulating tankers among them are fatigued tanker 
crews shipowners who give more priority to schedules than safety 
and inspectors who are overworked and burned out 
the center for marine conservation has called for a presidential 
task force to assess tanker safety because no agency is doing a 
toptobottom review it also criticized cutbacks in the coast 
guard as false economizing 
and despite the exxon valdez wreck that caused the nations 
worst oil spill on march 24 1989 the industry remains 
illprepared to handle a major spill and a glacialpaced congress 
still hasnt passed a tanker safety package 
the result is bleak news for a nation whose gluttonous appetite 
for oil means more tankers many of them aging will be pulling 
into its ports on any given day about 50 tankers carrying 450 
million gallons of oil sail into us harbors each one a potential 
environmental disaster 
we are asking for trouble said clifton curtis president of 
the oceanic society 
and not just environmentalists are uneasy 
this industry is in a bad way said arthur mackenzie head 
of the tanker advisory group and a former exxon corp shipping 
executive we have to make drastic changes in the way we build 
operate and license in this business 
whos studying the whole picture nobody 
in sheer numbers the coast guard investigated 265 oil spills 
from tankers last year an average of five a week most were minor 
but six were more than 10000 gallons including the 11 million 
gallons disgorged by the exxon valdez 
add last years 639 tank barge incidents and the average is 17 
a week 
a private study by golobs oil pollution bulletin in cambridge 
mass counted 78 spills of 10000 gallons or more in the past 12 
years an average of nearly seven a year 
total spillage was 41 million gallons at the same time 243 
billion gallons or 9998 percent of the oil shipped got to shore 
safely 
the oil industry says that record hardly supports the image of 
an oceanic demolition derby but six major spills have occurred 
already this year and the public as much as it demands the oil 
wont tolerate the sliming of beaches and shorelines 
what was an acceptable level of performance 10 years ago is 
not acceptable today said sean connaughton of the american 
petroleum institute theres an almost zero tolerance for oil 
spills the sensitivity is so much greater now 
environmentalists say the breakdowns are not isolated incidents 
but examples of common problems the way three mile island was in 
the nuclear power industry and the challenger explosion was in the 
space industry 
clearly this is an issue that has reached and will exceed 
crisis proportions the potential for an increasing number and more 
severe accidents is very high said roger mcmanus president of 
the center for marine conservation 
what we have on the seas is something we wouldnt put up with 
in air traffic he said it desperately needs attention 
turning things around is trickier than steering a supertanker in 
a tight channel there is no one solution because there is no one 
problem and no one agency who can fix it 
each branch of congress passed its own version of an oil tanker 
safety bill last fall but a 100member conference named to 
reconcile the differences had met just once before the mega borg 
exploded june 9 and leaked 39 million gallons of oil 
on july 12 the committee reached a compromise that would 
require new tankers be built with punctureresistant double hulls 
whileexisting tankers be fitted with a second hull or phased out of 
service over the next 20 years 
in addition the bill would create a 1 billion oil spill 
response fund make it easier for the coast guard to take over 
cleanup efforts set liability levels for spills and toughen 
licensing requirements for tanker crew members 
a final vote is pending 
</TEXT>
