<TEXT>
meanwhile the coast guard motto is semper paratus or 
always prepared but in an interview its commandant said the 
service would be better suited to live up to its motto if congress 
acts 
there is more that can be done were less prepared without 
this bill conceded adm j william kime we need to do 
everything we can to minimize the probability were going to have a 
spill and then maximize our ability to limit the impact of the 
pollution 
the coast guard in a 44page report by its tanker safety study 
group said a review of tanker operations has not been done in 10 
years 
among the highlights of the report distributed last fall to all 
admirals were 
tankers are being driven harder and faster by shipowners more 
concerned with schedules than safety the coast guard pays too much 
attention to owners desires to make money and too little attention 
to safety coast guard inspectors are overworked and burned out by 
a dirty and tiring job and their training is inadequate 
tankers are built with 18 percent less steel than in the 1970s 
newer ships are so big only 20 percent of the inside of their cargo 
tanks are inspected 
the report said the best way to avoid shipwrecks is having 
competent crews because human error plays a part in 90 percent of 
the groundings and collisions and 75 percent of the fires and 
explosions 
cuts in the number of crew have severely impaired routine 
maintenance the report said and relying on automation and 
machines as a cureall misses the point and provides a false 
sense of security 
fatigue is also factor when coast guard inspectors met with 
chief mates to set up inspections some mates were so exhausted 
they fell asleep during these meetings 
the center for marine conservation did its own study called 
shipping safety and americas coasts it urged presidential 
