<TEXT>
smallbusiness optimism about the immediate 
future faded in june to the lowest level for that month in at least 
four years 
in reporting survey results of more than 700 detailed responses 
from small businesses economist william dunkelberg said declines 
were noted in all but two of 10 components of a socalled optimism 
index 
the index produced for the national federation of independent 
business declined to a reading of 1001 sixtenths of a point 
below its yearago reading and more than two points below june 
readings in 1986 1987 and 1988 
the report confirms the weakness observed in other business 
surveys but it found little evidence among federation members that 
a credit squeeze was responsible 
however dunkelberg dean of temple universitys school of 
business in philadelphia said only 35 percent of reporting 
companies said they were regular borrowers a near record low for 
the survey which was begun in 1974 
the index is based on a formula that includes plans opinions 
and hard data on factors such as expected business conditions 
expected sales volume the climate for expansion job openings and 
hiring and spending plans 
the study found declines in plans for capital spending hiring 
and investment in larger inventories the labor market weakened 
slightly but both the pace of price increases and plans to raise 
prices declined 
the june optimism reading was also the lowest of 1990 although 
slightly lower readings were measured last october november and 
december 
while the optimism index measures results and attitudes of 
mostly small businesses although small can mean companies 
with more than 100 million in sales some economy watchers feel 
it is a responsive grassroots tool 
dunkelberg notes for example that the business community 
represented by the survey employs about onehalf the private 
nonfarm work force and produces about 50 percent of the nations 
gross private sector product 
using 1978 as its base of 100 the index plunged to a quarterly 
low of just 811 in the second quarter of 1980 but rebounded even 
more sharply to 951 in the third quarter of that year foretelling 
the rise from recession 
by 1983 the index was regularly over 100 reaching an alltime 
high of 1087 in the first quarter of 1984 since the second 
quarter of 1984 it has wavered between 995 and 1027 
while the survey found no evidence of a credit crunch it found 
suggestions of tighter lending practices causing dunkelberg to 
comment that while there is more selectivity this should be 
expected at the peak of a business cycle 
he observed that projects that may have looked good to lenders 
at the beginning of the expansion might not appear to have the same 
promise late in the expansion especially in real estate 
development 
thus with the same standards projects that were accepted 
earlier will now be turned down he said 
