<DOCNO> AP900717-0190 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a congressional study says investors should 
not be misled into believing personal financial advisers are 
closely watched by the securities and exchange commission 
investment advisers and financial planners must register with 
the sec and submit to periodic review if they advise on securities 
or issue analyses of securities 
but the sec doesnt guarantee that investment advisers know what 
theyre doing 
a study by the general accounting office released monday found 
that the sec was behind in reviewing registered advisers when 
advisers are reviewed usually only inadequate disclosure or 
recordkeeping problems are uncovered and the sec does little to 
ensure deficiencies are corrected the report said 
under the 1940 investment advisers act the sec requires 
investmentadvisers to register with the agency and submit to 
periodic review information submitted at registration is not 
verified until the first review which could take up to a year or 
more the gao report said 
secs oversight of investment advisers provides investors 
little assurance that the information they receive from advisers is 
accurate or that advisers operate in accordance with the law 
according to the gao study 
the sec however noted that to implement the reports 
recommendations would require tripling the staff now devoted to 
investment adviser review 
the gao the accounting arm of congress warned that current law 
unless improved may be doing more harm than good by lulling 
investors into a false sense of security that secregistered 
advisers have a seal of approval 
the study noted that one investor who lost her life savings of 
60000 said she had been impressed that the investment adviser 
was registered with the sec the investor was not identified in the 
report 
in a letter attached to the report sec officials said they do 
not have enough money and people to adequately regulate the 
financial advice industry 
recently between 2000 and 3000 new advisers have registered 
annually to inspect all new registrants within one year of 
registration would require a very large increase in staff 
resources kathryn b mcgrath who was then head of the secs 
division of investment management wrote the gao in an april 23 
letter 
she noted that the average sec examiner is able to complete 
about 25 inspections a year and in 1990 the current division staff 
of 53 expects to complete about 1330 examinations 
a hearing on the issue is scheduled for wednesday before the 
house energy and commerce committees finance subcommittee which 
requested the gao study 
rep rick boucher dva a member of the subcommittee has 
submitted a bill that would require anyone offering investment 
advice for pay to register with the sec and provide clients with 
accurate information the bill also would give customers the right 
to sue for damages when they lose money because of violations of 
the law 
this report sounds a warning bell for the millions of 
americans who consult financial planners each year boucher said 
in a statement issued jointly with reps edward markey dmass 
and dennis eckart dohio 
last year the sec submitted legislation that would farm out 
investment adviser oversight to a selfregulatory organization like 
the national association of securities dealers that has yet to be 
acted on 
the gao study noted that since 1980 the number of investment 
advisers has tripled to about 14000 while the assets they manage 
have increased from 440 billion 10 years ago to about 46 
trillion today 
while the amount of fraud and abuse reported to date has been 
relatively small compared to the amount of assets managed the gao 
worried that the threefold increase in the number of people 
providing financial advice and the 10fold increase in assets 
managed raises the risk that fraud and abuse will occur and the 
potential that any amounts lost could be large 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

