<TEXT>
roundtheclock meetings during the weekend 
produced an agreement between southland corp and some of its 
creditors that will pay cash to junk bond holders and give them a 
larger share of a restructured company 
but some analysts questioned if the sweetened deal which also 
calls for a larger cash infusion from japanese investors can save 
the 7eleven convenience store chain owner burdened by huge debts 
after a 49 billion leveraged buyout in 1987 
no ones been able to prove to me yet why it wouldnt be 
better to throw them into bankruptcy said jay lustig who 
follows distressed companies for drake capital securities inc in 
santa monica calif 
the agreement is the latest revision in a plan first announced 
in march that involved a bailout by itoyokado co ltd and 
seveneleven japan co ltd a majorityowned subsidiary 
southland missed 69 million in interest payments due june 15 
and a 30day grace period expired sunday during which the 
dallasbased company could have made the payments without penalty 
but weekend meetings between a committee of creditors the 
japanese investors and southland produced an agreement in principle 
on the restructuring spokeswoman cecilia stubbs norwood said 
monday 
the agreement replaces a proposal that would have paid holders 
of 18 billion in debt about 550 million plus stock and 
securities in the new company ms norwood said no value was 
immediately available on the revision 
also monday some bondholders filed a lawsuit in us district 
court in dallas asking that southland be forced to pay 69 million 
in interest payments it missed on june 15 the company reaffirmed 
monday that it would not make the payments leaving open the door 
for creditors to force southland into bankruptcy court 
