<TEXT>
a spurt in automobile production and a heat 
wave that boosted utility output pushed industrial production up 
04 percent in june the federal reserve reported tuesday 
last months 04 percent gain which followed a rise of 06 
percent in may surprised analysts who had been expecting a more 
modest increase 
the june increase helped push industrial production for the 
second quarter up by an annual rate of 35 percent a significant 
improvement over the mediocre 06 percent annual rate of gain in 
the first three months of the year 
however private analysts cautioned that the upturn was likely 
due to temporary factors rather than any longterm comeback in the 
nations manufacturing sector which has been in a slump for months 
analysts attributed much of the recent strength in auto 
production to the likelihood that automakers have been building up 
inventories in preparation for a possible september walkout by the 
united auto workers 
although the number is good its not necessarily a harbinger 
of strength in the months ahead the manufacturing sector is still 
in the doldrums said michael k evans who heads a washington 
economic forecasting company 
still cynthia latta of drimcgraw hill said the increase in 
industrial production showed were still slogging along with very 
slow growth but some growth 
manufacturing is not booming its struggling she said 
but since output does seem to be expanding slightly it has to be 
viewed as a relatively good report 
the fed said that the increases in automobile production and 
utility output accounted for threefourths of the total june 
increase 
the fed also reported the operating rate of the nations 
factories mines and utilities which usually move in tandem with 
industrial production rose 02 percentage point to 835 percent of 
capacity in june 
the operating rate measures not only output but changes in 
productivity levels 
while the june operating rate was the highest since decembers 
837 percent it was still well below the level a year ago when the 
industrial sector was operating at 846 percent of capacity 
industrial production at manufacturing plants making both 
durable and nondurable goods rose 05 percent in june after 
increasing 08 percent in may 
output of durable goods bigticket items expected to last at 
least three years also increased 05 percent after a jump of 13 
percent a month earlier manufacturing of nondurable goods such as 
food and clothing was up 04 percent after a 01 percent increase 
in may 
the fed said its industrial production index in june stood at 
1098 percent of its 1987 base up from 1093 in may 
