<TEXT>
the senate voted tuesday to speed up action on 
a major job discrimination bill brushing aside warnings from 
critics that the measure would lead to minority hiring quotas 
the action brought an outcry from republican leader bob dole 
that the bill was being rammed down our throats while white 
house chief of staff john sununu accused sponsors of backing out on 
a compromise reached last week 
if were going to be treated like a bunch of bums on this side 
of the aisle there wont be any agreements on anything said 
dole after the 6238 vote to limit debate to 30 hours 
provisions of the bill sponsored by sen edward m kennedy 
dmass range from a ban on racial harassment in the workplace to 
punitive damages for victims of intentional discrimination 
the sharpest clashes have come over a provision that would make 
it easier to challenge hiring practices of companies whose work 
forces do not mirror the racial and ethnic makeup of the local 
labor pool 
such employers if challenged in court would have to prove that 
the hiring practices that led to the composition of the work force 
were justified by business necessity that would reverse the most 
controversial of five 1989 supreme court rulings on job bias 
addressed by the bill 
the justices in a case involving a salmon cannery in alaska 
held that it was up to those who file such lawsuits to prove the 
practices they objected to were not motivated by business necessity 
the bush administration business groups and some gop senators 
say the bill would lead to employers using hiring quotas to avert 
any chance they would incur the costs including damage awards of 
job discrimination suits 
after voting to set the time limit the senate debated an 
alternative version of the legislation sponsored by sen nancy 
landon kassebaum rkan but it broke off action for the night with 
the administration and sponsors agreeing to negotiate some more 
while still allowing the clock to run on the 30hour deadline 
i think everybody agrees its worth one last shot one last 
effort dole said as the senate recessed bush said last week he 
was encouraged by the negotiations after kennedy and sununu 
appeared to reach a compromise 
i thought we had an agreement sununu said the senator 
came in yesterday after we had an agreement and then we didnt 
have it anymore 
he said president bush would continue to press for a civil 
rights agreement but would veto any measure that would lead to 
hiring quotas 
at a photo opportunity session earlier sununu said in answer a 
question on the chances of an agreement we had one thursday 
they reneged on it 
kennedy said on the senate floor however the president never 
claimed that there had been a deal and the situation was locked up 
and neither did i if anyone said otherwise he said they 
misspoke 
kennedy noted the indignation of critics of the bill who argued 
they needed more than 30 hours to purge it of what they viewed as 
quota provisions and other objectionable features 
i wish we could see that kind of indignation about the kind of 
unfairness that is taking place at job locations all over this 
country against women and minorities kennedy said 
dole grimly acknowledged the defection of eight republicans on 
the roll call raising his voice he suggested that perhaps someone 
else should be found to serve as minority leader 
some of our republicans they know better than the 
leadership he grumbled 
dole complained that sponsors were trying to portray republicans 
as opposed to civil rights because they voted in large part against 
limiting debate he said gop senators wanted a civil rights bill 
but remained concerned about the quota issues and other features of 
the bill 
to have this rammed down our throats because it didnt please 
the senator from massachusetts it seems to me that were going 
to be in for a long hot summer dole said 
to drive home the notion that republicans did not want to stand 
in the way of civil rights dole brought a sudden stunned silence 
in the senate by offering to approve the measure immediately on a 
voice vote immediately 
now we have a chance to pass this historic legislation right 
now dole declared we can finish in 20 minutes 
majority leader george mitchell dmaine a proponent of the 
bill objected to three separate offers by dole to pass the measure 
immediately mitchell declared that senators who were scheduled to 
offer amendments under the 30hour time limit were entitled to a 
hearing on them 
but dole said the democratic reluctance to pass the bill 
immediately proved that it had some troublesome features that even 
proponents wanted out before they went home to explain the measure 
to voters 
now were told we cant vote because we have some fellas stuck 
out here on a limb and we need some cosmetic surgery dole said 
sen john c danforth rmo one of the republicans who 
supported limiting debate said he didnt believe that what we 
have just done furthers the cause of enacting this into law 
i am satisfied with the bill as is and i will vote for the 
bill as is but it is clear that this bill is not going to become 
law unless the president agrees to it danforth said 
republicans joining danforth in the vote to limit debate were 
james jeffords of vermont a cosponsor of the bill william cohen 
of maine david durenberger of minnesota mark hatfield of oregon 
john heinz and arlen specter of pennsylvania and bob packwood of 
oregon 
the one democrat to vote against limiting debate was james exon 
dneb 
